{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"yogaSutras","displayName":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali","version":"1.0","language":"English","edition":"Johnston Translation, 1912","primaryCategory":"Philosophy & Spirituality","subcategory":"Yoga","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"groupingLevels":["book"],"groupingLabels":["Book"],"sortPriority":46,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"devotional","audienceTags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","theme:meditation","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"itemCount":193,"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Yoga_Sutras.json"},"data":[{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-001","text":"OM: Here follows Instruction in Union. — Union, here as always in the Scriptures of India, means union of the individual soul with the Oversoul; of the personal consciousness with","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 1 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":1},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-002","text":"Union, spiritual consciousness, is gained through control of the — versatile psychic nature.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 2 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":2},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-003","text":"Then the Seer comes to consciousness in his proper nature. — Egotism is but the perversion of spiritual being.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 3 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":3},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-004","text":"Heretofore the Seer has been enmeshed in the activities of the","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 4 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":4},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-005","text":"The psychic activities are five; they are either subject or not — subject to the five hindrances (Book II, 3).","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 5 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":5},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-006","text":"These activities are: Sound intellection, unsound intellection, — predication, sleep, memory.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 6 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":6},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-007","text":"The elements of sound intellection are: direct observation, — inductive reason, and trustworthy testimony.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 7 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":7},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-008","text":"Unsound intellection is false understanding, not resting on a — perception of the true nature of things.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 8 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":8},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-009","text":"Predication is carried on through words or thoughts not resting on","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 9 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":9},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-010","text":"Sleep is the psychic condition which rests on mind states, all — material things being absent.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 10 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":10},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-011","text":"Memory is holding to mind-images of things perceived, without","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 11 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":11},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-012","text":"The control of these psychic activities comes through the right use — of the will, and through ceasing from self-indulgence.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 12 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":12},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-013","text":"The right use of the will is the steady, effort to stand in","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 13 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":13},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-014","text":"This becomes a firm resting-place, when followed long, — persistently, with earnestness.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 14 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":14},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-015","text":"Ceasing from self-indulgence is conscious mastery over the thirst — for sensuous pleasure here or hereafter.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 15 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":15},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-016","text":"The consummation of this is freedom from thirst for any mode of — psychical activity, through the establishment of the spiritual man.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 16 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":16},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-017","text":"Meditation with an object follows these stages: first, exterior — examining, then interior judicial action, then joy, then realization of individual being.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 17 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":17},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-018","text":"After the exercise of the will has stilled the psychic activities, — meditation rests only on the fruit of former meditations.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 18 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":18},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-019","text":"Subjective consciousness arising from a natural cause is possessed — by those who have laid aside their bodies and been absorbed into subjective nature.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 19 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":19},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-020","text":"For the others, there is spiritual consciousness, led up to by — faith, valour, right mindfulness, one-pointedness, perception.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 20 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":20},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-021","text":"Spiritual consciousness is nearest to those of keen, intense will. — The image used is the swift impetus of the torrent; the kingdom must be taken by force.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 21 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":21},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-022","text":"The will may be weak, or of middle strength, or intense. — Therefore there is a spiritual consciousness higher than this.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 22 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":22},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-023","text":"Or spiritual consciousness may be gained by ardent service of the","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 23 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":23},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-024","text":"The Master is the spiritual man, who is free from hindrances, — bondage to works, and the fruition and seed of works.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 24 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":24},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-025","text":"In the Master is the perfect seed of Omniscience. — The Soul of the Master is in essence one with the Oversoul, and therefore partaker of the Oversoul’s all-wisdom and all-power.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 25 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":25},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-026","text":"He is the Teacher of all who have gone before, since he is not","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 26 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":26},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-027","text":"His word is OM. — OM: the symbol of the Three in One, the three worlds in the Soul; the three times, past, present, future, in Eternity; the three Divine","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 27 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":27},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-028","text":"Let there be soundless repetition of OM and meditation thereon. — This has many meanings, in ascending degrees.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 28 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":28},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-029","text":"Thence come the awakening of interior consciousness, and the","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 29 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":29},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-030","text":"The barriers to interior consciousness, which drive the psychic — nature this way and that, are these: sickness, inertia, doubt, lightmindedness, laziness, intemperance, false notions, inability to","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 30 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":30},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-031","text":"Grieving, despondency, bodily restlessness, the drawing in and — sending forth of the life-breath also contribute to drive the psychic nature to and fro.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 31 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":31},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-032","text":"Steady application to a principle is the way to put a stop to","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 32 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":32},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-033","text":"By sympathy with the happy, compassion for the sorrowful, delight — in the holy, disregard of the unholy, the psychic nature moves to gracious peace.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 33 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":33},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-034","text":"Or peace may be reached by the even sending forth and control of","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 34 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":34},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-035","text":"Faithful, persistent application to any object, if completely — attained, will bind the mind to steadiness.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 35 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":35},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-036","text":"As also will a joyful, radiant spirit. — There is no such illusion as gloomy pessimism, and it has been truly said that a man’s cheerfulness is the measure of his faith.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 36 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":36},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-037","text":"Or the purging of self-indulgence from the psychic nature. — We must recognize that the fall of man is a reality, exemplified in our own persons.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 37 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":37},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-038","text":"Or a pondering on the perceptions gained in dreams and dreamless","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 38 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":38},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-039","text":"Or meditative brooding on what is dearest to the heart. — Here is a thought which our own day is beginning to grasp: that love is a form of knowledge; that we truly know any thing or any person, by","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 39 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":39},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-040","text":"Thus he masters all, from the atom to the Infinite. — Newton was asked how he made his discoveries.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 40 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":40},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-041","text":"When the perturbations of the psychic nature have all been stilled, — then the consciousness, like a pure crystal, takes the colour of what it rests on, whether that be the perceiver, perceiving, or the thing","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 41 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":41},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-042","text":"When the consciousness, poised in perceiving, blends together the — name, the object dwelt on and the idea, this is perception with exterior consideration.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 42 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":42},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-043","text":"When the object dwells in the mind, clear of memory-pictures, — uncoloured by the mind, as a pure luminous idea, this is perception without exterior or consideration.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 43 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":43},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-044","text":"The same two steps, when referring to things of finer substance, — are said to be with, or without, judicial action of the mind.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 44 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":44},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-045","text":"Subtle substance rises in ascending degrees, to that pure nature — which has no distinguishing mark.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 45 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":45},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-046","text":"The above are the degrees of limited and conditioned spiritual — consciousness, still containing the seed of separateness.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 46 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":46},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-047","text":"When pure perception without judicial action of the mind is — reached, there follows the gracious peace of the inner self.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 47 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":47},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-048","text":"In that peace, perception is unfailingly true. — The poet, the wise philosopher and the saint not only reach a wide and luminous consciousness, but they gain certain knowledge of substantial","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 48 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":48},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-049","text":"The object of this perception is other than what is learned from — the sacred books, or by sound inference, since this perception is particular.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 49 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":49},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-050","text":"The impress on the consciousness springing from this perception — supersedes all previous impressions.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 50 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":50},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-051","text":"When this impression ceases, then, since all impressions have — ceased, there arises pure spiritual consciousness, with no seed of separateness left.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book I, Sutra 51 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book I","sutranumber":51},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-052","text":"The practices which make for union with the Soul are: fervent — aspiration, spiritual reading, and complete obedience to the Master.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 1 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":1},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-053","text":"Their aim is, to bring soul-vision, and to wear away hindrances. — The aim of fervour, spiritual reading and obedience to the Master, is, to bring soulvision, and to wear away hindrances.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 2 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":2},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-054","text":"These are the hindrances: the darkness of unwisdom, self-assertion, — lust hate, attachment.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 3 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":3},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-055","text":"The darkness of unwisdom is the field of the others. These — hindrances may be dormant, or worn thin, or suspended, or expanded.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 4 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":4},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-056","text":"Self-assertion comes from thinking of the Seer and the instrument of — vision as forming one self.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 6 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":6},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-057","text":"Lust is the resting in the sense of enjoyment. — This has been explained again and again.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 7 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":7},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-058","text":"Hate is the resting in the sense of pain. — Pain comes, for the most part, from the strife of personalities, the jarring discords between psychic selves, each of which deems itself","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 8 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":8},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-059","text":"Attachment is the desire toward life, even in the wise, carried — forward by its own energy.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 9 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":9},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-060","text":"These hindrances, when they have become subtle, are to be removed","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 10 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":10},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-061","text":"Their active turnings are to be removed by meditation. — Here is, in truth, the whole secret of Yoga, the science of the soul.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 11 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":11},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-062","text":"The burden of bondage to sorrow has its root in these hindrances. — It will be felt in this life, or in a life not yet manifested.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 12 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":12},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-063","text":"From this root there grow and ripen the fruits of birth, of the — life-span, of all that is tasted in life.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 13 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":13},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-064","text":"These bear fruits of rejoicing, or of affliction, as they are — sprung from holy or unholy works.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 14 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":14},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-065","text":"To him who possesses discernment, all personal life is misery, — because it ever waxes and wanes, is ever afflicted with restlessness, makes ever new dynamic impresses in the mind; and because all its","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 15 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":15},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-066","text":"This pain is to be warded off, before it has come. — In other words, we cannot cure the pains of life by laying on them any balm.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 16 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":16},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-067","text":"The cause of what is to be warded off, is the absorption of the","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 17 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":17},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-068","text":"Things seen have as their property manifestation, action, inertia. — They form the basis of the elements and the sense-powers.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 18 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":18},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-069","text":"The grades or layers of the Three Potencies are the defined, the — undefined, that with distinctive mark, that without distinctive mark.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 19 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":19},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-070","text":"The Seer is pure vision. Though pure, he looks out through the","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 20 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":20},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-071","text":"The very essence of things seen is, that they exist for the Seer. — The things of outer life, not only material things, but the psychic man also, exist in very deed for the purposes of the Seer, the Soul, the","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 21 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":21},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-072","text":"Though fallen away from him who has reached the goal, things seen — have not alto fallen away, since they still exist for others.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 22 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":22},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-073","text":"The association of the Seer with things seen is the cause of the — realizing of the nature of things seen, and also of the realizing of the nature of the Seer.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 23 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":23},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-074","text":"The cause of this association is the darkness of unwisdom. — The darkness of unwisdom is the absorption of consciousness in the personal life, and in the things seen by the personal life.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 24 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":24},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-075","text":"The bringing of this association to an end, by bringing the — darkness of unwisdom to an end, is the great liberation; this is the Seer’s attainment of his own pure being.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 25 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":25},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-076","text":"A discerning which is carried on without wavering is the means of","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 26 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":26},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-077","text":"His illuminations is sevenfold, rising In successive stages. — Patanjali’s text does not tell us what the seven stages of this illumination are.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 27 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":27},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-078","text":"From steadfastly following after the means of Yoga, until impurity — is worn away, there comes the illumination of thought up to full discernment.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 28 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":28},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-079","text":"The eight means of Yoga are: the Commandments, the Rules, right — Poise, right Control of the life-force, Withdrawal, Attention, Meditation, Contemplation.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 29 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":29},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-080","text":"The Commandments are these: nom injury, truthfulness, abstaining — from stealing, from impurity, from covetousness.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 30 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":30},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-081","text":"The Commandments, not limited to any race, place, time or occasion, — universal, are the great obligation.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 31 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":31},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-082","text":"The Rules are these: purity, serenity fervent aspiration, spiritual — reading, and per feet obedience to the Master.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 32 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":32},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-083","text":"When transgressions hinder, the weight of the imagination should be — thrown’ on the opposite side.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 33 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":33},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-084","text":"Transgressions are injury, falsehood, theft, incontinence, envy; — whether committed, or caused, or assented to, through greed, wrath, or infatuation; whether faint, or middling, or excessive; bearing endless,","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 34 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":34},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-085","text":"Where non-injury is perfected, all enmity ceases in the presence of — him who possesses it.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 35 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":35},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-086","text":"When he is perfected in truth, all acts and their fruits depend on","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 36 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":36},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-087","text":"Where cessation from theft is perfected, all treasures present — themselves to him who possesses it.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 37 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":37},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-088","text":"For him who is perfect in continence, the reward is valour and","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 38 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":38},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-089","text":"Where there is firm conquest of covetousness, he who has conquered — it awakes to the how and why of life.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 39 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":39},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-090","text":"Through purity a withdrawal from one’s own bodily life, a ceasing — from infatuation with the bodily life of others.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 40 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":40},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-091","text":"To the pure of heart come also a quiet spirit, one-pointed thought, — the victory over sensuality, and fitness to behold the Soul.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 41 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":41},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-092","text":"From acceptance, the disciple gains happiness supreme. — One of the wise has said: accept conditions, accept others, accept yourself.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 42 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":42},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-093","text":"The perfection of the powers of the bodily vesture comes through — the wearing away of impurities, and through fervent aspiration.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 43 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":43},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-094","text":"Through spiritual reading, the disciple gains communion with the — divine Power on which his heart is set.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 44 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":44},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-095","text":"Soul-vision is perfected through perfect obedience to the Master. — The sorrow and darkness of life come of the erring personal will which sets itself against the will of the Soul, the one great Life.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 45 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":45},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-096","text":"Right poise must be firm and without strain. — Here we approach a section of the teaching which has manifestly a two-fold meaning.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 46 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":46},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-097","text":"Right poise is to be gained by steady and temperate effort, and by — setting the heart upon the everlasting.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 47 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":47},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-098","text":"The fruit of right poise is the strength to resist the shocks of — infatuation or sorrow.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 48 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":48},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-099","text":"When this is gained, there follows the right guidance of the — life-currents, the control of the incoming and outgoing breath.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 49 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":49},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-100","text":"The life-current is either outward, or inward, or balanced; it is — regulated according to place, time, number; it is prolonged and subtle.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 50 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":50},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-101","text":"The fourth degree transcends external and internal objects. — The inner meaning seems to be that, in addition to the three degrees of control already described, control, that is, over the incoming current","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 51 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":51},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-102","text":"Thereby is worn away the veil which covers up the light. — The veil is the psychic nature, the web of emotions, desires, argumentative trains of thought, which cover up and obscure the truth","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 52 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":52},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-103","text":"Thence comes the mind’s power to hold itself in the light. — It has been well said, that what we most need is the faculty of spiritual attention; and in the same direction of thought it has been","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 53 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":53},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-104","text":"The right Withdrawal is the disengaging of the powers from — entanglement in outer things, as the psychic nature has been withdrawn and stilled.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 54 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":54},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-105","text":"Thereupon follows perfect mastery over the powers. — When the spiritual condition which we have described is reached, with its purity, poise, and illuminated vision, the spiritual man is coming","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 55 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":55},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-106","text":"The binding of the perceiving consciousness to a certain region is","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book II, Sutra 1 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book II","sutranumber":1},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-107","text":"A prolonged holding of the perceiving consciousness in that region — is meditation (dhyana).","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 2 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":2},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-108","text":"When the perceiving consciousness in this meditative is wholly given — to illuminating the essential meaning of the object contemplated, and is freed from the sense of separateness and personality, this is","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 3 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":3},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-109","text":"When these three, Attention, Meditation Contemplation, are exercised — at once, this is perfectly concentrated Meditation (sanyama).","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 4 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":4},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-110","text":"By mastering this perfectly concentrated Meditation, there comes the — illumination of perception.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 5 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":5},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-111","text":"This power is distributed in ascending degrees. — It is to be attained step by step.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 6 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":6},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-112","text":"This threefold power, of Attention, Meditation, Contemplation, is — more interior than the means of growth previously described.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 7 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":7},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-113","text":"But this triad is still exterior to the soul vision which is — unconditioned, free from the seed of mental analyses.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 8 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":8},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-114","text":"One of the ascending degrees is the development of Control. First — there is the overcoming of the mind-impress of excitation.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 9 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":9},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-115","text":"Through frequent repetition of this process, the mind becomes — habituated to it, and there arises an equable flow of perceiving consciousness.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 10 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":10},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-116","text":"The gradual conquest of the mind’s tendency to flit from one object — to another, and the power of one-pointedness, make the development of Contemplation.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 11 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":11},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-117","text":"When, following this, the controlled manifold tendency and the — aroused one-pointedness are equally balanced parts of the perceiving consciousness, his the development of one-pointedness.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 12 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":12},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-118","text":"Through this, the inherent character, distinctive marks and — conditions of being and powers, according to their development, are made clear.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 13 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":13},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-119","text":"Every object has its characteristics which are already quiescent, — those which are active, and those which are not yet definable.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 14 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":14},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-120","text":"Difference in stage is the cause of difference in development. — This but amplifies what has just been said.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 15 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":15},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-121","text":"Through perfectly concentrated Meditation on the three stages of — development comes a knowledge of past and future.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 16 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":16},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-122","text":"The sound and the object and the thought called up by a word are — confounded because they are all blurred together in the mind.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 17 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":17},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-123","text":"When the mind-impressions become visible, there comes an — understanding of previous births.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 18 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":18},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-124","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on mind-images is gained the — understanding of the thoughts of others.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 19 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":19},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-125","text":"But since that on which the thought in the mind of another rests is — not objective to the thought-reader’s consciousness, he perceives the thought only, and not also that on which the thought rests.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 20 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":20},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-126","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on the form of the body, by — arresting the body’s perceptibility, and by inhibiting the eye’s power of sight, there comes the power to make the body invisible.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 21 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":21},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-127","text":"The works which fill out the life-span may be either immediately or","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 22 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":22},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-128","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on sympathy, compassion and — kindness, is gained the power of interior union with others.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 23 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":23},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-129","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on power, even such power as — that of the elephant may be gained.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 24 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":24},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-130","text":"By bending upon them the awakened inner light, there comes a — knowledge of things subtle, or concealed, or obscure.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 25 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":25},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-131","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on the sun comes a knowledge","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 26 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":26},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-132","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on the moon comes a knowledge — of the lunar mansions.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 27 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":27},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-133","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on the fixed pole-star comes a — knowledge of the motions of the stars.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 28 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":28},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-134","text":"Perfectly concentrated Meditation on the centre of force in the — lower trunk brings an understanding of the order of the bodily powers.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 29 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":29},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-135","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on the centre of force in the — well of the throat, there comes the cessation of hunger and thirst.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 30 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":30},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-136","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation on the centre of force in the — channel called the “tortoise-formed,” comes steadfastness.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 31 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":31},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-137","text":"Through perfectly concentrated Meditation on the light in the head — comes the vision of the Masters who have attained.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 32 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":32},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-138","text":"Or through the divining power of tuition he knows all things. — This is really the supplement, the spiritual side, of the Sutra just translated.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 33 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":33},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-139","text":"The personal self seeks to feast on life, through a failure to — perceive the distinction between the personal self and the spiritual man.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 35 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":35},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-140","text":"Thereupon are born the divine power of intuition, and the hearing, — the touch, the vision, the taste and the power of smell of the spiritual man.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 36 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":36},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-141","text":"These powers stand in contradistinction to the highest spiritual","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 37 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":37},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-142","text":"Through the weakening of the causes of bondage, and by learning the — method of sassing, the consciousness is transferred to the other body.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 38 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":38},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-143","text":"Through mastery of the upward-life comes freedom from the dangers — of water, morass, and thorny places, and the power of ascension is gained.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 39 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":39},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-144","text":"By mastery of the binding-life comes radiance. — In the Upanishads, it is said that this binding-life unites the upward-life to the downward-life, and these lives have their analogies","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 40 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":40},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-145","text":"From perfectly concentrated Meditation on the correlation of — hearing and the ether, comes the power of spiritual hearing.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 41 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":41},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-146","text":"By perfectly concentrated Meditation em the correlation of the body — with the ether, and by thinking of it as light as thistle-down, will come the power to traverse the ether.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 42 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":42},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-147","text":"When that condition of consciousness is reached, which is — far-reaching and not confined to the body, which is outside the body and not conditioned by it, then the veil which conceals the light is","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 43 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":43},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-148","text":"Mastery of the elements comes from perfectly concentrated — Meditation on their five forms: the gross, the elemental, the subtle, the inherent, the purposive.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 44 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":44},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-149","text":"Thereupon will come the manifestation of the atomic and other — powers, which are the endowment of the body, together with its unassailable force.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 45 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":45},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-150","text":"Shapeliness, beauty, force, the temper of the diamond: these are — the endowments of that body.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 46 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":46},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-151","text":"Mastery over the powers of perception and action comes through — perfectly concentrated Meditation on their fivefold forms; namely, their power to grasp their distinctive nature, the element of","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 47 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":47},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-152","text":"Thence comes the power swift as thought, independent of — instruments, and the mastery over matter.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 48 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":48},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-153","text":"When the spiritual man is perfectly disentangled from the psychic — body, he attains to mastery over all things and to a knowledge of all.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 49 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":49},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-154","text":"By absence of all self-indulgence at this point, when the seeds of — bondage to sorrow are destroyed, pure spiritual being is attained.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 50 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":50},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-155","text":"There should be complete overcoming of allurement or pride in the — invitations of the different realms of life, lest attachment to things evil arise once more.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 51 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":51},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-156","text":"From perfectly concentrated Meditation on the divisions of time and — their succession comes that wisdom which is born of discernment.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 52 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":52},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-157","text":"Hence comes discernment between things which are of like nature, — not distinguished by difference of kind, character or position.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 53 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":53},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-158","text":"The wisdom which is born of discernment is starlike; it discerns — all things, and all conditions of things, it discerns without succession: simultaneously.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 54 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":54},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-159","text":"When the vesture and the spiritual man are alike pure, then perfect — spiritual life is attained.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 55 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":55},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-160","text":"Psychic and spiritual powers may be inborn, or they may be gained by — the use of drugs, or by incantations, or by fervour, or by Meditation.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 1 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":1},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-161","text":"The transfer of powers from one venture to another comes through the — flow of the natural creative forces.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book III, Sutra 2 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book III","sutranumber":2},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-162","text":"The apparent, immediate cause is not the true cause of the creative — nature-powers; but, like the husbandman in his field, it takes obstacles away.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 3 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":3},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-163","text":"Vestures of consciousness are built up in conformity with the Boston — of the feeling of selfhood.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 4 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":4},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-164","text":"In the different fields of manifestation, the Consciousness, though — one, is the elective cause of many states of consciousness.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 5 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":5},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-165","text":"Among states of consciousness, that which is born of Contemplation — is free from the seed of future sorrow.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 6 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":6},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-166","text":"The works of followers after Union make neither for bright pleasure — nor for dark pain The works of others make for pleasure or pain, or a mingling of these.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 7 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":7},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-167","text":"From the force inherent in works comes the manifestation of those — dynamic mind images which are conformable to the ripening out of each of these works.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 8 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":8},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-168","text":"Works separated by different nature, or place, or time, are brought — together by the correspondence between memory and dynamic impression.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 9 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":9},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-169","text":"The series of dynamic mind-images is beginningless, because Desire","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 10 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":10},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-170","text":"Since the dynamic mind-images are held together by impulses of — desire, by the wish for personal reward, by the substratum of mental habit, by the support of outer things desired; therefore, when these","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 11 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":11},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-171","text":"The difference between that which is past and that which is not yet — come, according to their natures, depends on the difference of phase of their properties.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 12 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":12},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-172","text":"These properties, whether manifest or latent, are of the nature of","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 13 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":13},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-173","text":"The external manifestation of an object takes place when the — transformations ore in the same phase.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 14 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":14},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-174","text":"The paths of material things and of states of consciousness are — distinct, as is manifest from the fact that the same object may produce different impressions in different minds.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 15 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":15},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-175","text":"Nor do material objects depend upon a single mind, for how could — they remain objective to others, if that mind ceased to think of them?","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 16 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":16},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-176","text":"An object is perceived, or not perceived, according as the mind is, — or is not, tinged with the colour of the object.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 17 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":17},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-177","text":"The movements of the psychic nature are perpetually objects of — perception, since the Spiritual Man, who is the lord of them, remains unchanging.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 18 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":18},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-178","text":"The Mind is not self-luminous, since it can be seen as an object. — This is a further step toward overthrowing the tyranny of the “mind”: the psychic nature of emotion and mental measuring.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 19 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":19},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-179","text":"Nor could the Mind at the same time know itself and things external","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 20 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":20},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-180","text":"If the Mind be thought of as seen by another more inward Mind, then — there would be an endless series of perceiving Minds, and a confusion of memories.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 21 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":21},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-181","text":"When the psychical nature takes on the form of the spiritual — intelligence, by reflecting it, then the Self becomes conscious of its own spiritual intelligence.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 22 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":22},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-182","text":"The psychic nature, taking on the colour of the Seer and of things — seen, leads to the perception of all objects.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 23 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":23},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-183","text":"The psychic nature, which has been printed with mind-images of — innumerable material things, exists now for the Spiritual Man, building for him.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 24 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":24},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-184","text":"For him who discerns between the Mind and the Spiritual Man, there — comes perfect fruition of the longing after the real being of the Self.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 25 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":25},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-185","text":"Thereafter, the whole personal being bends toward illumination,","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 26 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":26},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-186","text":"In the internals of the batik, other thoughts will arise, through — the impressions of the dynamic mind-images.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 27 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":27},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-187","text":"These are to be overcome as it was taught that hindrances should be","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 28 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":28},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-188","text":"He who, after he has attained, is wholly free from self, reaches — the essence of all that can be known, gathered together like a cloud.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 29 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":29},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-189","text":"Thereon comes surcease from sorrow and the burden of toil. — Such a one, it is said, is free from the bond of Karma, from the burden of toil, from that debt to works which comes from works done in","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 30 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":30},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-190","text":"When all veils are rent, all stains washed away, his knowledge — becomes infinite; little remains for him to know.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 31 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":31},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-191","text":"Thereafter comes the completion of the series of transformations of — the three nature potencies, since their purpose is attained.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 32 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":32},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-192","text":"The series of transformations is divided into moments. When the — series is completed, time gives place to duration.","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 33 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":33},{"id":"yoga-sutra-pg-193","text":"Pure spiritual life is, therefore, the inverse resolution of the — potencies of Nature, which have emptied themselves of their value for the Spiritual man; or it is the return of the power of pure","author":"Patanjali","source":"Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, Book IV, Sutra 34 (Johnston trans., 1912)","tags":["tradition:hindu","tradition:yoga","language:en","theme:meditation","theme:mind","theme:consciousness","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Johnston 1912 translation. Project Gutenberg PG 2526, public domain.","book":"Book IV","sutranumber":34}]}